# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decentralized-finance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] CFMMs display pools of liquidity of two assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The takers and providers of liquidity interact in the liquidity pools: LPs deposit their assets in the pool and LTs exchange assets directly with the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] CFMMs rely on two rules; the LT trading condition and the LP provision condition.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The LT trading condition links the state of the pool before and after a trade is executed, and it determines the relative prices between the assets by their quantities in the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The LP provision condition links the state of the pool before and after liquidity is deposited or withdrawn by an LP.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Thus, the trading function establishes the link between liquidity and prices, so LTs can compute the execution costs of their trades as a function of the trade size, and LPs can compute the exact quantities that they deposit.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] In CFMMs, both conditions state that price formation happens only through LT trades (see below).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] In decentralized platforms running on peer-to-peer networks, CFMMs are hard-coded and immutable programs implemented as Smart Contracts, where LPs and LTs invoke the code of the contract to execute their transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] A particular case of CFMMs are the constant product market makers (CPMMs) such as Uniswap v2 and Uniswap v3 where the trading function uses the product of the quantities of each asset in the pool to determine clearing prices.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] CFMMs are also popular in prediction markets.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] An early description of a CFMM was published by economist Robin Hanson in *"Logarithmic Market Scoring Rules for Modular Combinatorial Information Aggregation"* (2002).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Early literature referred to the broader class of "automated market makers", including that of the Hollywood Stock Exchange founded in 1999; the term "constant-function market maker" was introduced in *"Improved Price Oracles: Constant Function Market Makers"* (Angeris & Chitra 2020).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] First be seen in production on a Minecraft server in 2012, CFMMs are a popular DEX architecture.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Consider a reference asset X and an asset Y which is valued in terms of X .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Assume that the liquidity pool of the CFMM initially consists of quantity x of asset X and quantity y of asset Y .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The pair $(x,y)$ is referred to as the **reserves** of the pool (the following definitions can be extended to a basket of more than two assets).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The CFM is characterised by a **trading function** $f:\mathbb {R} ^{+}\times \mathbb {R} ^{+}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ (also known as the invariant) defined over the pool reserves x and y .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The trading function is continuously differentiable and increasing in its arguments ( $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ denotes the set of positive real numbers).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] For instance, the trading function of the constant product market maker (CPMM) is $f(x,y)=x\times y$ .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Other types of CFMMs are the constant sum market maker with $f(x,y)=x+y$ ; the constant mean market maker with $f(x,y)=w_{x}x+w_{y}y$ , where $w_{x},w_{y}>0$ and $w_{x}+w_{y}=1$ ; and the hybrid function market maker, which uses combinations of trading functions.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] LT transactions involve exchanging a quantity $\Delta ^{y}$ of asset Y for a quantity $\Delta ^{x}$ of asset X , and vice-versa.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] where $\kappa$ is the *depth* of the pool (see the **LP provision condition** below) and is a measure of the available liquidity.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The value of the depth $\kappa >0$ is constant before and after a trade is executed, so the LT trading condition **(1)** defines a level curve.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] For a fixed value of the depth $\kappa$ , the **level function** $\varphi _{\kappa }$ (also known as the forward exchange function ) is such that $f(x,y)=\kappa ^{2}\iff x=\varphi _{\kappa }(y)$ .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] For any value $\kappa$ of the depth, the level function $\varphi _{\kappa }:\mathbb {R} ^{+}\mapsto \mathbb {R} ^{+}$ is twice differentiable.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The LT trading condition **(1)** links the state of the pool before and after a liquidity taking trade is executed.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] It is proven that no roundtrip arbitrage in a CFMM implies that the level function $\varphi$ must be convex.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Execution costs in the CFMM are defined as the difference between the marginal exchange rate and the exchange rate at which a trade is executed.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] It has been shown that LTs can use the convexity of the level function around the pool's reserves level to approximate the execution costs $\left|{\tilde {Z}}(\Delta ^{y})-Z\right|$ by ${\frac {1}{2}}\,\varphi _{\kappa }^{''}(y)\left|\Delta ^{y}\right|$ .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] LP transactions involve depositing or withdrawing quantities $(\Delta ^{x},\Delta ^{y})$ of asset X and asset Y .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Let $\varphi _{\kappa _{0}}$ and $\varphi _{\kappa _{1}}$ be the level functions corresponding to the values $\kappa _{0}$ and $\kappa _{1}$ , respectively.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Denote by Z the initial marginal exchange rate of the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The LP provision condition **(2)** links the state of the pool before and after a liquidity provision operation is executed.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The trading function $f(x,y)$ is increasing in the pool reserves x and $y.$ So, when liquidity provision activity increases (decreases) the size of the pool, the value of the pool's depth $\kappa$ increases (decreases).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The value of $\kappa$ can be seen as a measure of the liquidity depth in the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Note that the LP provision condition holds for any homothetic trading function.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] In CPMMs, the liquidity provision condition is $x/y=(x+\Delta ^{x})/(y+\Delta ^{y})$ when the quantities $(\Delta ^{x},\Delta ^{y})$ are deposited to the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Thus, liquidity is provided so that the proportion of the reserves x and y in the pool is preserved.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] For LPs, the key difference between the traditional markets based on LOBs and CFMMs is that in LOBs, market makers post limit orders above and below the mid-price to earn the spread on roundtrip trades, while in CFMMs, LPs earn fees paid by LTs when their liquidity is used.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Without fees paid by LTs, liquidity provision in CFMMs is a **loss-leading activity**.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Loss-Versus-Rebalancing (LVR) is a popular measure of these losses.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] To thoroughly characterise their losses, LPs can also use **Predictable Loss (PL)**, which is a comprehensive and model-free measure for the unhedgeable and predictable losses of liquidity provision.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] One source of PL is the **convexity cost** (losses due to adverse selection, they can be regarded as generalized LVR) whose magnitude depends on liquidity taking activity and the convexity of the level function.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The other source is the **opportunity cost**, which is incurred by LPs who lock assets in the pool instead of investing them in the risk-free asset.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] where $\left(\xi _{t}\right)_{t\in [0,T]}$ is an increasing stochastic process with initial value 0 , and $\left(y_{t}\right)_{t\in [0,T]}$ is a process that describes the reserves in asset Y .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] PL can be estimated without specifying dynamics for the marginal rate or the trading flow and without specifying a parametric form for the level function.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] PL shows that liquidity provision generates losses for any type of LT trading activity (informed and uninformed).
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The level of fee revenue must exceed PL in expectation for liquidity provision to be profitable in CFMMs.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Impermanent loss, or divergence loss, is sometimes used to characterise the risk of providing liquidity in a CFMM.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Impermanent loss compares the evolution of the value of the LP's assets in the pool with the evolution of a self-financing buy-and-hold portfolio invested in an alternative venue.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The self-financing portfolio is initiated with the same quantities $\left(x_{0},y_{0}\right)$ as those that the LP deposits in the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] where $y_{t}$ are the reserves in asset Y in the pool at time t .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The convexity of the level function shows that ${\text{IL}}_{t}\leq 0$ .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] where $Z_{t}$ is the marginal exchange rate in the CPMM pool at time t .
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] ${\text{IL}}$ is not an appropriate measure to characterise the losses of LPs because it can underestimate or overestimate the losses that are solely imputable to liquidity provision.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] More precisely, the alternative buy-and-hold portfolio is not exposed to the same market risk as the holdings of the LP in the pool, and the impermanent loss can be partly hedged.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] In contrast, PL is the predictable and unhedgeable component in the wealth of LPs.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Concentrated liquidity is a feature introduced by Uniswap v3 for CPMMs.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The key feature of a CPMM pool with CL is that LPs specify a range of exchange rates in which to post liquidity.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] The bounds of the liquidity range take values in a discretised finite set of exchange rates called ticks.
[src:decentralized-finance/constant-function-market-maker] Concentrating liquidity increases fee revenue, but also increases PL and *concentration risk*, i.e., the risk of the exchange rate exiting the range.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] A core principle of DeFi is its accessibility.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] By operating on public blockchains, DeFi applications (commonly referred to as "dApps") enable users from across the globe to access financial services without the need for a centralized authority or compliance with traditional Know Your Customer (KYC) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] DeFi also introduces programmability and composability to finance.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Developers can create interoperable financial products by combining different DeFi protocols like building blocks, a concept often referred to as "money Legos".
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (abbreviated DEXs) are alternative payment ecosystems that use new protocols for financial transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] They emerged within decentralized finance (DeFi), a sector of blockchain technology and fintech.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Centralized exchanges (CEXs), DEXs and DEX aggregators are all built on a multi-layered DeFi architecture, with each layer serving a well-defined purpose.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] (See Figure: *Multi-layered Architecture of the DeFi Stack*).
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] While they share common components of the first four layers, such as *the Settlement layer*, *Asset layer*, *Protocol layer* and *Application layer*, DEX aggregators have an additional component or *Aggregator layer*, which allows them to connect and interact with other DEXs via smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The Ethereum blockchain popularized smart contracts, which are the basis of DeFi, in 2017.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Other blockchains have since implemented smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Alternative Layer 1 protocols, such as Radix, have been developed utilizing sharded consensus mechanisms to attempt to resolve scalability issues inherent in earlier blockchains.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] As of 2021, MakerDAO was a prominent lending DeFi platform based on a stablecoin that was established in 2017.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] It allowed users to borrow DAI, a token pegged to the US dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Through a set of smart contracts that govern the loan, repayment, and liquidation processes, MakerDAO aimed to maintain the stable value of DAI in a decentralized and autonomous manner.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In September 2024, MakerDAO rebranded as Sky, and its stablecoin DAI was renamed USDS.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] As of March 2025, the combined circulating supply of DAI and USDS stood at approximately US$9 billion.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In June 2020, Compound Finance, a decentralized finance protocol enabling users to lend or borrow cryptocurrency assets and which provides typical interest payments to lenders, started rewarding lenders and borrowers with a cryptocurrency called Comp.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] This token, which is used for running Compound, can also be traded on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In July 2020, *The Washington Post* described decentralized finance techniques and the risks involved.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In September 2020, Bloomberg said that DeFi made up two-thirds of the cryptocurrency market in terms of price changes and that DeFi collateral levels had reached $9 billion.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Ethereum saw a rise in developers during 2020 due to the increased interest in DeFi.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Total collateral levels across DeFi protocols reached a peak of $178 billion in November 2021, before declining to under $40 billion by 2023 amid broader downturns in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] DeFi has attracted venture capitalists such as Andreessen Horowitz and Michael Novogratz.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The evolution of Decentralized Finance (DeFi) began with Bitcoin in 2009 and matured with Ethereum’s 2015 launch, which introduced smart contracts and enabled decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] By 2021, DeFi protocols such as MakerDAO, Compound, Aave, and Uniswap had driven total value locked (TVL) to over $180 billion.The 2022 crypto market crash, which followed events like the collapse of Terra/LUNA and FTX, exposed critical vulnerabilities in the DeFi space and triggered a downturn.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] A key trend was the tokenization of real-world assets (RWA) such as treasury bills, real estate, and carbon credits.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Platforms like MakerDAO and Centrifuge enabled institutional investors to access on-chain yield tied to off-chain assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Layer 2 scaling solutions such as Arbitrum and Optimism also gained traction, reducing transaction fees and increasing throughput on top of Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] This period also marked the rise of intent-based DeFi, allowing users to specify desired outcomes, with protocols handling transaction logic (Bankless, 2023).
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In 2024, regulatory developments shaped DeFi's evolution.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The European Union’s MiCA framework (Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation) came into effect, impacting stablecoin issuers and custodial services.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In response, many DeFi projects began adopting hybrid models, combining decentralized architecture with off-chain compliance layers to navigate legal requirements.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Meanwhile, interoperability improved with the deployment of cross-chain bridges like Wormhole V2 and Chainlink CCIP, enabling liquidity to flow between Ethereum, Solana, Avalanche, and other ecosystems.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] DeFi revolves around decentralized applications, also known as DApps, that perform financial functions on distributed ledgers called blockchains, a technology that was made popular by Bitcoin and has since been adapted more broadly.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Rather than transactions being made through a centralized intermediary such as a cryptocurrency exchange or a traditional securities exchange, transactions are directly made between participants, mediated by smart contract programs.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] These smart contracts, or DeFi protocols, typically run using open-source software that is built and maintained by a community of developers.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] DApps are typically accessed through a browser extension or application.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] For example, MetaMask allows users to directly interact with Ethereum through a digital wallet.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Many of these DApps can be linked to create complex financial services.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Examples include lending protocols, in which stablecoin holders can lend assets such as USD Coin or DAI to a liquidity pool in a borrow/lending protocol such as the Aave protocol, and allow others to borrow those digital assets by depositing their own collateral.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The protocol automatically adjusts interest rates based on the demand for the asset.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Some DApps source external (off-chain) data, such as the price of an asset, through blockchain oracles.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Aave Protocol popularized "flash loans", which are uncollateralized loans of an arbitrary amount that are taken out and paid back within a single blockchain transaction.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Max Wolff is credited with the original invention of flash loans with the original implementation released in 2018 by Marble Protocol.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Many exploits of DeFi platforms have used flash loans to manipulate cryptocurrency spot prices.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Another DeFi protocol is Uniswap, which is a decentralized exchange (DEX) set up to trade tokens issued on Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Rather than using a centralized exchange to fill orders, Uniswap pays users to form liquidity pools in exchange for a percentage of the fees collected from traders swapping tokens in and out of the liquidity pools.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Because no centralized party runs Uniswap (the platform is governed by its users), and any development team can use the open-source software, there is no entity to check the identities of the people using the platform and meet KYC/AML regulations.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] As of 2020, it was not clear what position regulators would take on the legality of such platforms; subsequent regulatory developments are summarised in the Regulation section.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (DEX) are a type of cryptocurrency exchange, which allow for either direct peer-to-peer, or Automated Market Maker (AMM) liquidity pool cryptocurrency transactions to take place without the need for an intermediary.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The lack of an intermediary differentiates them from centralized exchanges (CEX).
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In transactions made through decentralized exchanges, the typical third party entities which would normally oversee the security and transfer of assets (e.g. banks, stockbrokers, online payment gateways, government institutions, etc.) are substituted by a blockchain or distributed ledger.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Some common methods of operation include the use of smart contracts or order book relaying –although numerous other variations are possible, with differing degrees of decentralization.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Because traders on a decentralized exchange often do not need to transfer their assets to the exchange before executing a trade, decentralized exchanges reduce the risk of theft from hacking of exchanges, but liquidity providers do need to transfer tokens to the decentralized exchange.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are also more anonymous than exchanges that implement know your customer (KYC) requirements.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] As of 2018, there were signs that decentralized exchanges had been suffering from low trading volumes and reduced market liquidity.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The 0x project, a protocol for building decentralized exchanges with interchangeable liquidity, attempted to solve this issue.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] As of mid‑2025, weekly trading volume on decentralized exchanges (DEXs) averaged around $18.6 billion, with more than 9.7 million unique wallets interacting with DeFi protocols.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Due to a lack of KYC processes, and no way to revert a transaction, users are at a loss if they are ever hacked for their passwords or private keys.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Liquidity providers staking in DeFi protocols may also suffer an impermanent loss when the relative value of the deposited token pair has shifted by the time the deposit is withdrawn.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Although liquidity pool DEX are the most widely used, they may have some drawbacks.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The most common problems of liquidity pool DEXes are market price impact, slippage, and front running.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Price impact arises from the design of automated market makers: the larger the trade, the greater its effect on the pool's prevailing price.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] For example, if the constant product AMM is in use, every deal must keep the product xy = k constant, where x and y are quantities of two cryptocurrencies (or tokens) in the pool.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Price impact is non-linear, so the larger is the input amount Δx, the lower is the final ratio y / x that gives an exchange price.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The problem is mostly significant for relatively large deals versus the liquidity pool size.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Front running is a special type of attack in public blockchains when some participant (usually a miner) seeing an upcoming trading transaction puts his own transaction ahead (playing with a transaction fee for example), making the initial transaction less profitable or even reverted.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] To provide some protection against front running attacks, many DeFi exchanges offer a slippage tolerance option for end-users.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] This setting allows users to set a limit on the worst acceptable execution price relative to the price observed at the time of transaction signing; if the executed price would breach that limit, the transaction reverts.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are particularly exposed to cyberattacks, and DEX-related incidents account for a major share of crypto-exchange losses.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In 2025, at least 20 incidents were reported, resulting in aggregate losses of $535 million.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Decentralized Finance protocols exhibit varying degrees of decentralization, which largely depend on the architecture of their underlying smart contracts and external dependencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] When the protocol's smart contracts are deployed statically, such that the protocol's logic cannot be altered and no access-restricted functions are present, they may potentially function as neutral infrastructure.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Conversely, if the smart contracts are upgradeable or permit the modification of key parameters, or if key functions are restricted to a specific set of users, this neutrality can be compromised.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] A decentralized exchange can still have centralized components, whereby some control of the exchange is still in the hands of a central authority.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The governance of a DeFi platform, typically as part of a Decentralized Autonomous Organization, is done through tokens that grant voting rights and are distributed amongst participants.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] However, the majority of these tokens are often held by few individuals and are rarely used to vote.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In July 2018, the decentralized exchange Bancor was reportedly hacked and suffered a loss of $23.5 million in assets before freezing funds.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In a Twitter tweet, Charlie Lee, the creator of Litecoin, spoke out and claimed an exchange cannot be decentralized if it can lose or freeze customer funds.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Operators of decentralized exchanges can face legal consequences from government regulators.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] One example is the founder of EtherDelta, who in November 2018 settled charges with the U.S.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Securities and Exchange Commission over operating an unregistered securities exchange.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Coding errors and hacks are common in DeFi.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Blockchain transactions are irreversible, which means that an incorrect or fraudulent DeFi transaction cannot be corrected easily if at all.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] The person or entity behind a DeFi protocol may be unknown and may disappear with investors' money.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Investor Michael Novogratz has described some DeFi protocols as "Ponzi-like".
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] DeFi has been compared to the initial coin offering craze of 2017, part of a cryptocurrency bubble.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Inexperienced investors are at particular risk of losing money because of the sophistication required to interact with DeFi platforms and the lack of any intermediary with customer support.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] On the other hand, as the code for DeFi smart contracts is generally open-source software that can be copied to set up competing platforms, experienced users and user-created bots might create instabilities as funds shift between platforms which share the same code.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In addition, DeFi platforms might inadvertently provide incentives for cryptocurrency miners to destabilize the system.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Illicit actors, including cyber criminals, fraudsters and terrorist organisations, are exploiting the technical complexity of DeFi and the absence of AML/CFT checks to launder criminal proceeds or raise funds and crypto-assets to finance criminal activity.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] They use DeFi to obscure the movement of funds through various techniques and services.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In 2021, half of cryptocurrency crime was related to DeFi.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] This rise has been attributed to a combination of developer incompetence and non-existent or poorly enforced regulations.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] Theft from DeFi can come from either external hackers stealing from vulnerable projects, or "rug pulls", where the developers and influencers promote a project and then take the money, as a form of pump-and-dump.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] In October 2021, the FATF included DeFi in the guidance for crypto service providers, making the authority's aim to regulate this type of asset.
[src:decentralized-finance/decentralized-finance] They are expecting each individual country to determine if individuals involved in DeFi can be considered a virtual asset provider and be subjected to the FATF's guidelines.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:decentralized-finance/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A **stablecoin** is a type of cryptocurrency that aims to maintain a stable value relative to a specified asset, a pool or basket of assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The specified asset might refer to fiat currency, commodity, or other cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Despite the name, stablecoins are not necessarily stable.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins rely on stabilization tools such as reserve assets or algorithms that match supply and demand to try to maintain a stable value.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Historically, multiple stablecoins have failed to maintain their value relative to the underlying assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] With a growing number of market transactions involving stablecoins, their issuance and usage are increasingly regulated by governments around the world.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins emerged in 2014 as a method for investors in cryptocurrencies to park their money when they invest in other highly volatile cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins are now mainly used for buying or selling cryptoassets, and for making cross-border payments.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to the Bank for International Settlements in July 2025, 90% of the market capitalization of stablecoins was either in Tether or USDC.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to the Financial Action Task Force, the market capitalization of stablecoins reached $316 billion in October 2025, while daily trading volume reached $156 billion.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Within the stablecoin market, 95% of them are backed by fiat currency, while 97% among those fiat currency-backed stablecoins are denominated in US dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Fiat-backed stablecoins are stablecoins that are backed by assets denominated in a fiat currency.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The value of a fiat-backed stablecoin is based on the value of the backing currency, which is supposedly held by a third party custodian.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The issuer defends the peg of the stablecoin by holding mostly fiat-denominated short-term assets, such as treasury bonds, high-quality commercial paper, repurchase agreements and bank deposits.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Therefore, the structure of fiat-backed stablecoins closely resembles that of money market funds (MMFs), and they are exposed to similar risk of large-scale redemption requests causing negative contagion effects on the financial system.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] As of October 2025, nearly 97% of fiat-backed stablecoins are pegged to the US dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Major examples of US-dollar-pegged stablecoins are Tether's USDT and Circle's USDC.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] For Euro-pegged stablecoins, examples include Circle's EURC, EUR Tether, and Stasis EUR.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Cryptocurrency-backed stablecoins are stablecoins using other cryptocurrencies as collateral.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The reason such stablecoins are created is that by utilizing smart contracts, they allow a decentralized network to track the price of the US dollar as closely as possible.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Another use case of cryptocurrency-backed stablecoins is to convert a cryptocurrency into ERC20 compatible standard to enable trading on another blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Commodity-backed stablecoins are stablecoins that are backed by commodities.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Algorithmic stablecoins, sometimes called seigniorage-style stablecoin, are stablecoins with no reserve assets or only partial reserve assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] They utilize algorithms that match supply and demand of the stablecoins to maintain a stable value.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The European Central Bank suggests that algorithmic stablecoins should be treated as unbacked crypto-assets.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Some major examples of algorithmic stablecoins are Celo Dollar, Tron's USDD and Kava's USDX.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins provide convenience for investors in cryptocurrencies, as a simpler way to buy and sell other more volatile cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] *Planet Money* has described this use of stablecoins as similar to casino chips, as they simplify buying and selling other cryptocurrencies before eventually being traded for money.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to a 2025 report from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), cross-border flows of stablecoin surpassed those of unbacked crypto assets in early 2022.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to the IMF, Asia and the Pacific region have the most stablecoin activity, while after adjusting for GDP, the majority of stablecoins flow from North America to other locations.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The report estimated that stablecoin cross-border flow was $1.4 trillion dollars in 2024, compared to the global cross-border payment market of approximately one quadrillion dollars.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In advanced economies, cross-border flows is dominated by traditional payment systems.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The largest share of stablecoins being used for cross-border transactions was among emerging markets and developing economies.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to a study by the University of Cambridge, the most cited reason for using stablecoins in cross-border settlement is the 24/7 settlement capability, allowing transactions to take place outside banking hours.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A 2025 study in the journal *Telematics and Informatics*, of 866 U.S.-based adults who had sent remittances within the previous year, 26% reported using stablecoins for cross-border transfers, with 34% also using other methods.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to Chainalysis, due to the volatility of the Venezuelan bolivar, some Venezuelans use US dollar-denominated stablecoins to preserve value and transact in a more stable currency.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In January 2026, it was reported that US dollar-denominated stablecoins are increasingly being used in domestic transactions in Venezuela due to prolonged period of hyperinflation, sanctions, and capital controls.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A report by Standard Chartered warned that the prevalence of US dollar-denominated stablecoins could potentially cause $1 trillion from developing countries to flow to stablecoins, causing loss of bank deposits.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The capital outflow would be caused by risk aversion of individuals within the developing countries against sudden sharp currency depreciation.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Since 2019, Oxfam began distributing humanitarian aid to residents of Vanutau using US dollar stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] By 2022, the project registered 35,000 people in the Pacific region and has distributed aid of around $2 million to participants.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to a report published by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in January 2026, the UNDP is running pilot programmes involving stablecoins in Columbia, Syria, Gambia, Papua New Guinea, Kazakhstan, and Morocco.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] For example, in Syria, the UNDP Cash-for-Work programmes experienced difficulty delivering stipends to Syrians due to lack of financial infrastructure, and so the UNDP is experimenting with sending stablecoins to the beneficiaries instead.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] According to media report in 2021, Portuguese nonprofit ImpactMarket reported distributing over $1 million in Celo Dollar stablecoins to more than 18,000 beneficiaries in 102 locations in Africa, and said some local merchants had begun accepting the tokens for payments.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In January 2024, the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) reported that stablecoins, particularly USDT, had become the cryptocurrency of choice for organized crime groups engaged in cyberfraud and money laundering in East and Southeast Asia.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Reuters reported in 2023 that groups designated as terrorist organizations by Israel, the United States and other countries were using stablecoins on the Tron blockchain instead of more volatile bitcoin tokens to preserve the value of transferred funds.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The intergovernmental Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has reported that stablecoins are increasingly used for illicit financial activity, including money laundering, terrorism financing, sanctions evasion, and proliferation financing.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The report states that stablecoins such as USDT (Tether) and USDC (Circle) provide a relatively stable medium for moving proceeds compared with more volatile cryptocurrencies, and that their liquidity, interoperability, and ease of cross-border transfer make them attractive for illicit use.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] After the passing of the GENIUS Act by the Trump administration in the United States, Jürgen Schaaf, adviser to the European Central Bank (ECB) wrote that widespread adoption of US dollar stablecoins could erode European monetary sovereignty and financial stability.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Scholars in China and Singapore have both described the GENIUS Act as a strategic move to increase demand for US Treasuries and therefore an attempt to consolidate the hegemony of the US dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Lesetja Kganyago, Governor of South African Reserve Bank, expressed that US dollar stablecoins are being used to undermine African currencies, and is concerned that some African countries might lose their monetary sovereignty.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Agnès Bénassy-Quéré, Deputy Governor of the Banque de France, and François Villeroy de Galhau, Governor of the Banque de France, warned that Europe's monetary sovereignty is threatened by US dollar-denominated stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In March 2026, a research published by the ECB examined the effect of foreign-currency-denominated stablecoins on the monetary sovereignty of Europe.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The adoption of US dollar-denominated stablecoins would import foreign monetary policies into Europe, weakening the ability of central banks to affect short-term interest rates, complicate liquidity management within the banking system, and increase exchange-rate-related volatility in funding flows.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In extreme cases, it could make Europe's own monetary policy tools ineffective.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In response to sanctions against Russian entities, A7A5, a rouble-pegged stablecoin, was launched by Promsvyazbank and Moldovan oligarch Ilan Șor.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The stablecoin was used by Russian businesses to conduct cross-border payments and by the Russian state to carry out an influence campaign.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In October 2025, the UN's Multilateral Sanctions Monitoring Team found that North Korea avoided sanctions by using stablecoin for sale and transfer of military equipment and raw materials.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The report alleged that North Korean officials sold military-grade satellite communications systems to a buyer in Laos and a portable air defense system to a buyer in Sudan.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In January 2026, it was reported that the Central Bank of Iran is accumulating stablecoins while facing sanctions against the Iranian regime.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] While stablecoins aim to maintain the peg with underlying assets, they are constantly traded on the market and therefore subject to market volatility.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A stablecoin can deviate from the peg due to a number of reasons, such as liquidity stress, increase in market demand, mismanagement of reserves, fluctuations in prices of other cryptocurrencies, design flaws of stabilization mechanic, etc.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Since fiat-backed stablecoins are structurally similar to money market funds, they pose similar contagion risk, in which a large amount of redemption caused the selling of underlying assets, further pushing down the price of the underlying assets and creating more demand for redemption.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Partner banks of stablecoin issuers would also face substantial increase in liquidity risk exposure due to linkage with fiat-backed stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Unlike money market funds, stablecoins are designed to be settlement instruments, and therefore may face more rapid conversion, resulting in increased liquidity risk.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Reserve-backed stablecoins require a third party custodian to hold the reserve assets to maintain price stability.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The concentration of reserve deposits creates a counterparty risk in which the custodian may fail in the case of a bank run.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In March 2023, the price of Circle's USDC de-pegged temporarily during the banking crisis in the United States in which Signature Bank, Silvergate Bank, and Silicon Valley Bank collapsed.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Fiat-backed stablecoins maintain the peg with underlying currency by using reserve assets such as US Treasuries.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Since the value of Treasuries are affected by interest rate, it is possible for stablecoins to become insolvent when interest rate increase.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Some stablecoin issuers mitigate this risk by allocating the majority of their backing asset into short duration securities which are less affected by interest rate.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In an analysis on IMF's Finance & Development, Professor Hélène Rey wrote that advancement in quantum computing is often ignored in the discussion of stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Quantum computers in the near future may be able to break public-key cryptography, allowing hackers to attack the currency networks used by stablecoins, potentially causing financial crises.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A research by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology pointed out that flaws in the logic of smart contracts could potentially result in stablecoin issuers losing control of the supply of stablecoins and their network.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Cross-chain bridges are another attack vector which can cause deposit and redemption issues.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Tether's USDT is currently the world's largest market capitalization stablecoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Tether initially claimed their stablecoin is fully backed by fiat currency.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] However, in October 2021, it failed to produce audits for reserves used to collateralize the quantity of minted USDT stablecoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Tether were fined $41 million by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) for deceiving consumers.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The CFTC found that Tether only had enough fiat reserves to guarantee their stablecoin for 27.6% of the time during 2016 to 2018.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Since then, Tether began issuing assurance reports on USDT backing, although some speculation persists regarding the use of Chinese commercial paper for reserves.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] As at February 2026, Tether had never completed an audit by an accounting firm.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Hyun-Song Shin, governor of the Bank of Korea, wrote in his research that since stablecoins on different blockchains are not interoperable, they create a fragmented ecosystem as compared to fiat money, which has the advantage of network effect.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The requirement of "gas fee" for transactions, and the increase in fee when traffic is high, creates a dilemma in which users are incentivized to switch to blockchains with lower fees, ensuring that the ecosystem is fragmented.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Algorithmic stablecoins are vulnerable to a de-pegging process known as "death spiral", in which an external event, such as the tightening of global liquidity, led to heavy redemption of the stablecoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] This triggered the minting of the linked token to burn the stablecoin, causing the supply of the linked token to increase exponentially, further causing a decrease in price.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A famous case of death spiral is the TerraUSD (UST), which was created by Terraform Labs founded by Do Kwon.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] TerraUSD was meant to maintain a 1:1 peg with the United States dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Instead of being backed by dollars, UST was designed to keep its peg by linking it with another Terra network token, LUNA.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The mechanism worked by providing an economic incentive for arbitrage.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] If UST lost its peg and traded below $1, an arbitrager could purchase it on the secondary market and redeem it for $1 worth of LUNA.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Correspondingly, if UST traded higher than $1, market actors could mint new UST by locking in $1 of LUNA and then sell the new UST on the market for a profit.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] However, this mechanism assumes there is sufficient market demand for UST and LUNA, making the stablecoin inherently fragile.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In May 2022, UST broke its peg with its price plunging to 10 cents, while LUNA fell to "virtually zero", down from an all-time high of $119.51.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The collapse wiped out almost $45 billion of market capitalization over the course of a week.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In the case of TerraUSD, another contributing factor to its failure was its proof-of-stake mechanism.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The fall in the price of LUNA caused validators to sell their stakes, allowing malign actors to become dominant validators.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] A stablecoin should not be confused with a central bank digital currency (CBDC).
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] CBDC is issued by central banks, meaning that they are a direct claim on the central bank, while stablecoin is issued by private entity.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Another difference is that CBDC, being issued by central banks, would belong to the monetary base (M0), while stablecoins issued by commercial financial institutions would belong to the monetary aggregate (M2).
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The European Central Bank's digital euro project has been under consideration since 2021 but has not been legislated by the European Parliament as of August 2025.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Christine Lagarde, president of European Central Bank, called it a "strategic priority" for Europe in response to US legislation of stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] While most stablecoins are non-interest bearing and therefore do not provide interest returns to the holder, some issuers and service providers began offering yield-bearing stablecoins in an attempt to gain market share.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The reason most stablecoins with centralized issuers do not provide interest return is because that would potentially make them financial securities, thus falling under regulatory regime.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The US's *GENIUS Act*, Europe's *MiCAR*, and Hong Kong's *Stablecoin Bill* all explicitly prohibit the provision of yield-bearing stablecoins by regulated issuers.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Australian regulator treats yield-bearing stablecoins as managed investment schemes.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In February 2026, media reported that legislation in the US regarding the provision of interest was stalled due to opposition from banks.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Some cryptoasset service providers (CASPs) such as trading platforms and market makers developed products for stablecoin users to earn interests.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] For example, a user can buy stablecoins through a trading platform and re-lent the bought stablecoins to the platform.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The platform then provides the stablecoins to institutional borrowers to earn interest.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The interest is passed to the user after subtracting the platform's margin.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The European Union and Hong Kong completely prohibit CASPs from offering yield on payment stablecoins, while Singapore restricted such products to institutional investors under limited conditions.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] While issuers may not directly provide interest return, decentralized financial platforms are another possible avenue for earning interests.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] By providing stablecoins for liquidity on decentralized platforms, holders of stablecoins can get a share of the fees paid by liquidity takers.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] This process is known as "yield farming".
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Contrary to popular belief, yield farming is not risk free, because the holders are engaged in lending activity.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In the case of the TerraUSD, initially to drive adoption, the Anchor protocol was created to offer a yield of 19.5% to depositors of the stablecoin, a rate much higher than the return on US Treasuries.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Thus, a large amount of the stablecoin is locked in the Anchor protocol.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Subsequently when the price of TerraUSD began to crash.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The holders are unable to cash out of their position and are left holding the bag.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The Central Bank of Armenia (CBA) has adopted the *Law on Crypto Assets* in 2025 to strengthen consumer protection in cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In addition, the CBA is trying to introduce regulations on issuance of stablecoins in 2026 with assistance from the IMF.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins in Australia are regulated by the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC).
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In December 2024, the ASIC published the "*Information Sheet 225 Crypto-assets*" (INFO 225), establishing the regulatory requirement of stablecoins under "*Corporations Act 2001*".
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Under the definition, issuers of stablecoin are treated as operating non-cash payment facilities; algorithmic stablecoins are treated as derivatives; while yield-bearing stablecoins are treated as managed investment schemes.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In September and December 2025, the ASIC issued exemptions to obtain licenses for intermediaries providing services related to stablecoins and distributing stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In July 2025, the Central Bank of Bahrain introduced the *Stablecoin Issuance and Offering (SIO) Module*.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Under the regulation, stablecoin issuers can issue single currency fiat-backed stablecoins pegged to the Bahraini Dinar, US dollar, or any other fiat currency upon obtaining approval of the central bank.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In November 2025, the Canadian government under Mark Carney announced in the Federal Budget 2025 of a proposed legislation to regulate the issuance of stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The legislation is expected to require issuers to maintain asset reserves, govern redemption policies, implement risk management frameworks, and protect personal information of Canadians.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The *Retail Payment Activities Act* will also be amended to enable regulation of payment service providers using stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The proposed legislation was made in direct response to the United States' legislation of the *GENIUS Act*.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Stablecoins are considered illegal in Mainland China.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The People's Bank of China, the central bank of China, also asked Chinese companies, including Ant Group and JD.com, to stop their plans to issue stablecoins in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region in October 2025.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The central bank further clarified in November 2025 that stablecoins are considered non-compliant with current regulation and asked regulatory bodies and law enforcement to crackdown on the use of stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In February 2026, the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) issued a notice banning the issuance of Renminbi-denominated stablecoins within and outside China, the reason being that currency issuance is a matter of sovereignty.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The European Union introduced the *Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation* (MiCAR) in June 2023.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The regulation became applicable to asset-referenced tokens and e-money tokens on 30 June 2024.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] MiCAR has no clear regulation on global firms issuing the same stablecoin both from an EU-regulated entity and from a third-country entity, causing concern that in that event of large scale redemption of a multi-country stablecoin, the reserves located in the EU might be quickly depleted.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In September 2025, a consortium of nine European banks announced the planned launch of a MiCAR compliant stablecoin in response to the dominance of US denominated stablecoins on the market.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In December 2024, Hong Kong gazetted its *Stablecoins Bill*.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), the regulatory body of stablecoins in Hong Kong, warned the public to "rein in the euphoria".
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In particular, guidelines require stablecoin issuers to have strict rules on anti-money laundering, risk management, and corporate governance.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In April 2026, the HKMA issued stablecoin licenses to HSBC and Standard Chartered.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In June 2022, Japan's Financial Services Agency launched the *Regulatory Framework for Crypto-assets and Stablecoins*.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The regulation requires stablecoin issuer of fiat-backed stablecoin (known as digital-money type stablecoins in Japan) to register with the agency.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The agency views algorithmic stablecoin as crypto assets and does not require issuer to register.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] However, intermediaries such as crypto exchanges are subject to regulations.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In August 2025, fintech company JPYC received approval by the agency to launch the first stablecoin pegged to the Japanese Yen.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The first yen-pegged stablecoin launched in October 2025.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In November 2025, Kyrgyzstan launched the first national stablecoin, USDKG.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The issuer is state-owned company Virtual Asset Issuer OJSC.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The stablecoin is backed by gold and pegged to the US dollar.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In September 2025, the Central Bank of Russia approved the stablecoin A7A5 as a digital financial asset which can be used by Russian importers and exporters for cross-border settlements.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In November 2023, the Monetary Authority of Singapore finalized its *Stablecoin Regulatory Framework* after conducting public consultation since October 2022.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Issuers of stablecoins are required to maintain a portfolio of reserve assets denominated in the currency of the stablecoin peg.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] On 16 November 2023, the regulator approved Paxos Digital and StraitsX as stablecoin issuers.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Regulations on the issuance of stablecoins in South Korea are being discussed.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In February 2026, Bank of Korea, the central bank of South Korea, suggested that only licensed commercial banks should be able to issue won-denominated stablecoins to alleviate concerns regarding money laundering and financial stability.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] However, the Financial Services Commission (FSC) suggested a more open approach on the participation of technology firms, arguing that a rigid approach would hinder innovation.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In June 2024, the Central Bank of the UAE established the *Payment Token Services Regulations* to regulate the use of stablecoins in the UAE.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The regulations prohibit persons within the UAE from accepting stablecoins for the sale of goods and services except licensed payment token.In April 2025, the sovereign wealth fund of Abu Dhabi, ADQ, and the First Abu Dhabi Bank, are set to launch a stablecoin backed by dirhams.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In February 2026, the central bank approved the dirham-backed stablecoin launched by the First Abu Dhabi Bank.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In October 2025, Andrew Bailey, governor of the Bank of England, announced that the Bank of England will publish a consultation paper on the UK's stablecoin regulation.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The regulation is set to apply to stablecoins used for day-to-day payments and those used for settling tokenized financial transaction.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Bailey is known to be a skeptic of stablecoin and once said stablecoins risked pulling money out of the banking system.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] The comments by Bailey drawn criticism from stablecoin issuer for constraining investment in the UK.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] Under the proposed regulation, individuals would be subject to a limit of holding £20,000 worth of stablecoins.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In February 2026, the Financial Conduct Authority, Britain's financial regulator, announced the use of a "sandbox" programme to trial stablecoin products in controlled conditions.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In June 2026, lawmakers in the House of Lords called for a softer regulation on stablecoins, especially regarding the cap on the stablecoin holdings of individuals and requirement on issuers to back tokens with non-interest-bearing deposits.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In July 2025, the United States passed the *GENIUS Act*, a bill which allows banks and other financial institutions to issue stablecoins backed by fiat currency or other high-quality collateral, such as US Treasuries.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] At the time of its passing, the bill was expected to generate greater demand for US Treasuries by stablecoin issuers.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In November 2025, Stephen Miran at the Federal Reserve Board of Governors, confirmed that stablecoins are already increasing demand for US Treasuries, and are "contributing to the dollar's dominance".
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] This would cause a decrease in the neutral rate of interest and lower borrowing cost for the US government.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] An estimate by the Bank for International Settlements using data from 2021 to 2025 found that demand for stablecoins lowers 3-month T-bill yields by about 2-2.5 basis points, an effect comparable to that of small-scale quantitative easing.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In March 2023, the Legislature of the State of Wyoming passed the *Wyoming Stable Token Act*, which established the Wyoming Stable Token Commission for the purpose of issuing stablecoin.
[src:decentralized-finance/stablecoin] In January 2026, the first state-backed stablecoin has been released in Wyoming.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] The protocol, which runs on open-source software, was launched in 2018.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] As of December 2024, Uniswap is estimated to be the largest decentralized exchange and the seventh-largest cryptocurrency exchange overall by daily trading volume.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap was created on November 2, 2018 by Hayden Adams, a former mechanical engineer at Siemens.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Adams is the founder and CEO of Uniswap Labs, the company responsible for the development of the **Uniswap Protocol**, a decentralized exchange (DEX) built on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Adams launched Uniswap in November 2018, after working as a mechanical engineer and being inspired by a blog post written by Vitalik Buterin, the co-founder of Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] His goal was to create a decentralized platform for exchanging tokens without relying on centralized exchanges.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap operates using open-source software on blockchain networks, and allows users to exchange cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Governance of the protocol is managed by holders of its native governance token, UNI, which was introduced in 2020 and distributed retroactively to early users.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] While UNI is used to vote on protocol upgrades and changes, it is not required to use the platform.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap introduced the Automated Market Maker (AMM) model, which allows users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap Labs is a software company founded in 2018 by Hayden Adams.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] The company's early investors included venture capital firms like Andreessen Horowitz, Paradigm Operations, Union Square Ventures LLC and ParaFi.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] In 2022 Uniswap Labs had raised $165 million, after announcing in 2021 that it was looking to raise between $100 and $200 million and was working with Polychain.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap offers products such as a self-custodial mobile wallet, a trading API for professional users, and a web interface.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] These tools provide access to liquidity across multiple blockchains, including Ethereum, Polygon, and Optimism.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] The Uniswap Foundation was founded in 2022 by Devin Walsh and Ken Ng, after 95% of Uniswap token holders voted in favor of the proposal.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] The Foundation facilitates community governance of the Uniswap DAO, development of the Uniswap Protocol, and communication among contributors.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap Foundation's most recent funding proposal, Uniswap Unleashed, outlined a plan to make the Uniswap Protocol the world’s infrastructure for digital value transfer with significant support for Uniswap v4 and Unichain.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Uniswap acts as an automated market maker and uses liquidity pools to fulfill orders, instead of relying on a traditional market maker, with an aim to create more efficient markets.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Individuals and bots—termed "liquidity providers"—provide liquidity to the exchange by adding a pair of tokens to a smart contract which can be bought and sold by other users according to the constant-product rule $\phi (x,y)=xy$ .
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] In return, liquidity providers are given a percentage of the trading fees earned for that trading pair.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] For each trade, a certain amount of tokens is removed from the pool for an amount of the other token, thereby changing the price.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] In December 2025, Uniswap governance approved the “UNIfication” proposal, enabling protocol fees (the “fee switch”) and introducing a deflationary mechanism tied to protocol revenue.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] UNI is the governance token of the Uniswap protocol, enabling holders to participate in the platform's decentralized governance.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] The token allows holders to propose and vote on protocol upgrades, changes to fee structures, and other governance-related matters.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] UNI operates on the Ethereum blockchain following the ERC-20 standard, ensuring compatibility with a wide range of decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-finance/uniswap] Its total supply is capped, with a scheduled release over several years to support ongoing development and ecosystem growth.
